      "variant": "main",
      "html": "<h4>Video: Acceptable Moves</h4>\n<p>Watch the following video to learn more about acceptable moves.&nbsp;</p>\n<video controls=\"true\" crossorigin=\"anonymous\">\n  <source src=\"https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/84fd718f1e7fa4c23f38cb1f2a45b7a21744d55f\">\n  <track default=\"true\" kind=\"captions\" label=\"On\" src=\"https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/86ba592db56095fbc646f9f369cf34545df8eb23 \" srclang=\"en_us\">https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/84fd718f1e7fa4c23f38cb1f2a45b7a21744d55f\n</video>\n<h4>Solving Equations and Creating Equivalent Equations</h4>\n<p>One way to create equivalent equations is to solve the equation. In each step of solving, an equivalent equation is created.</p>\n<p><span>Here is a general strategy for solving linear equations:</span></p>\n<strong>\n  <div align=\"left\" dir=\"ltr\">\n    <table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\">\n      <colgroup>\n        <col width=\"139\">\n        <col width=\"485\">\n      </colgroup>\n      <tbody>\n        <tr>\n          <td>\n            <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Step 1</span></p>\n          </td>\n          <td>\n            <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Simplify each side of the equation as much as possible.<br>\n              </span></p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><span>Use the Distributive Property to remove any parentheses.</span></li>\n              <li><span>Combine like terms.</span></li>\n            </ul>\n          </td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n          <td>\n            <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Step 2</span></p>\n          </td>\n          <td>\n            <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Collect all the variable terms on one side of the equation.<br>\n              </span></p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><span>Use the Addition or Subtraction Property of Equality.</span></li>\n            </ul>\n          </td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n          <td>\n            <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Step 3</span></p>\n          </td>\n          <td>\n            <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Collect all the constant terms on the other side of the equation.<br>\n              </span></p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><span>Use the Addition or Subtraction Property of Equality.</span></li>\n            </ul>\n          </td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n          <td>\n            <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Step 4&nbsp;</span></p>\n          </td>\n          <td>\n            <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Make the coefficient of the variable term equal to 1.<br>\n              </span></p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><span>Use the Multiplication or Division Property of Equality.</span></li>\n              <li><span>State the solution to the equation.</span></li>\n            </ul>\n          </td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n          <td>\n            <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Step 5</span></p>\n          </td>\n          <td>\n            <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Check the solution.&nbsp;<br>\n              </span></p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><span>Substitute the solution into the original equation to make sure the result is a true statement.</span></li>\n            </ul>\n          </td>\n        </tr>\n      </tbody>\n    </table>\n  </div>\n</strong>\n<p><span><br>Here is an example of solving equations. Notice that each step is an acceptable move that creates an equivalent equation.&nbsp;</span></p>\n<div data-type=\"example\" id=\"fs-id1166503246595\">\n  <div data-type=\"exercise\" id=\"fs-id1166503439330\">\n    <div data-type=\"solution\" id=\"fs-id1166503414798\">\n      <span data-alt=\"This figure is a table that has three columns and five rows. The first column is a header column, and it contains the names and numbers of each step. The second column contains further written instructions. The third column contains math. On the top row of the table, the first cell on the left reads: &ldquo;Step 1. Simplify each side of the equation as much as possible.&rdquo; The text in the second cell reads: &ldquo;Use the Distributive Property. Notice that each side of the equation is simplified as much as possible.&rdquo; The third cell contains the equation negative 6 times x plus 3, where x plus 3 is in parentheses, equals 24. Below this is the same equation with the negative 6 distributed across the parentheses: negative 6x minus 18 equals 24.\" data-type=\"media\" id=\"fs-id1166503550871\">\n        <img alt=\"This figure is a table that has three columns and five rows. The first column is a header column, and it contains the names and numbers of each step. The second column contains further written instructions. The third column contains math. On the top row of the table, the first cell on the left reads: &ldquo;Step 1. Simplify each side of the equation as much as possible.&rdquo; The text in the second cell reads: &ldquo;Use the Distributive Property. Notice that each side of the equation is simplified as much as possible.&rdquo; The third cell contains the equation negative 6 times x plus 3, where x plus 3 is in parentheses, equals 24. Below this is the same equation with the negative 6 distributed across the parentheses: negative 6x minus 18 equals 24.\" data-media-type=\"image/jpeg\" id=\"4\" src=\"https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/dd7c9e7d8b039c8c094eff8e357c91d4566695a8\">\n      </span>\n      <span data-alt=\"In the second row of the table, the first cell says: &ldquo;Step 2. Collect all variable terms on one side of the equation.&rdquo; In the second cell, the instructions say: &ldquo;Nothing to do&mdash;all x&rsquo;s are on the left side. The third cell is blank.\" data-type=\"media\" id=\"fs-id1166503588359\">\n        <img alt=\"In the second row of the table, the first cell says: &ldquo;Step 2. Collect all variable terms on one side of the equation.&rdquo; In the second cell, the instructions say: &ldquo;Nothing to do&mdash;all x&rsquo;s are on the left side. The third cell is blank.\" data-media-type=\"image/jpeg\" id=\"5\" src=\"https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/72e79c005d953ac6e0b48084d5fd61d9d27572f9\">\n      </span>\n      <span data-alt=\"In the third row of the table, the first cell says: &ldquo;Step 3. Collect constant terms on the other side of the equation. In the second cell, the instructions say: &ldquo;To get constants only on the right, add 18 to each side. Simplify.&rdquo; The third cell contains the same equation with 18 added to both sides: negative 6x minus 18 plus 18 equals 24 plus 18. Below this is the equation negative 6x equals 42.\" data-type=\"media\" id=\"fs-id1166503595352\">\n        <img alt=\"In the third row of the table, the first cell says: &ldquo;Step 3. Collect constant terms on the other side of the equation. In the second cell, the instructions say: &ldquo;To get constants only on the right, add 18 to each side. Simplify.&rdquo; The third cell contains the same equation with 18 added to both sides: negative 6x minus 18 plus 18 equals 24 plus 18. Below this is the equation negative 6x equals 42.\" data-media-type=\"image/jpeg\" id=\"6\" src=\"https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/4331b8a0fa8111b5f861075c2e839e6e90358fb7\">\n      </span>\n      <span data-alt=\"In the fourth row of the table, the first cell says: &ldquo;Step 4. Make the coefficient of the variable term equal to 1.&rdquo; In the second cell, the instructions say: &ldquo;Divide each side by negative 6. Simplify. The third cell contains the same equation divided by negative 6 on both sides: negative 6x over negative 6 equals 42 over negative 6, with &ldquo;divided by negative 6&rdquo; written in red on both sides. Below this is the answer to the equation: x equals negative 7.\" data-type=\"media\" id=\"fs-id1166503436790\">\n        <img alt=\"In the fourth row of the table, the first cell says: &ldquo;Step 4. Make the coefficient of the variable term equal to 1.&rdquo; In the second cell, the instructions say: &ldquo;Divide each side by negative 6. Simplify. The third cell contains the same equation divided by negative 6 on both sides: negative 6x over negative 6 equals 42 over negative 6, with &ldquo;divided by negative 6&rdquo; written in red on both sides. Below this is the answer to the equation: x equals negative 7.\" data-media-type=\"image/jpeg\" id=\"7\" src=\"https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/4d60f4138afd48c38518b8fb1f629eb8d43639db\">\n      </span>\n      <span data-alt=\"In the fifth row of the table, the first cell says: &ldquo;Step 5. Check the solution.&rdquo; In the second cell, the instructions say: &ldquo;Let x equal negative 7. Simplify. Multiply.&rdquo; In the third cell, there is the instruction: &ldquo;Check,&rdquo; and to the right of this is the original equation again: negative 6 times x plus 3, with x plus 3 in parentheses, equal 24. Below this is the same equation with negative 7 substituted in for x: negative 6 times negative 7 plus 3, with negative 7 plus 3 in parentheses, might equal 24. Below this is the equation negative 6 times negative 4 might equal 24. Below this is the equation 24 equals 24, with a check mark next to it.\" data-type=\"media\" id=\"fs-id1166503410270\">\n        <img alt=\"In the fifth row of the table, the first cell says: &ldquo;Step 5. Check the solution.&rdquo; In the second cell, the instructions say: &ldquo;Let x equal negative 7. Simplify. Multiply.&rdquo; In the third cell, there is the instruction: &ldquo;Check,&rdquo; and to the right of this is the original equation again: negative 6 times x plus 3, with x plus 3 in parentheses, equal 24. Below this is the same equation with negative 7 substituted in for x: negative 6 times negative 7 plus 3, with negative 7 plus 3 in parentheses, might equal 24. Below this is the equation negative 6 times negative 4 might equal 24. Below this is the equation 24 equals 24, with a check mark next to it.\" data-media-type=\"image/jpeg\" id=\"8\" src=\"https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/293124cfb59934acad8d28ff582858ad1d84136f\">\n      </span>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><br></p>\n<div class=\"howto\" data-type=\"note\" id=\"fs-id1166503317199\">\n  <div data-type=\"title\"><strong><span>Summary:</span></strong></div>\n  <div data-type=\"title\"><span>Ways to create an equivalent equation:</span><br></div>\n  <div data-type=\"title\">\n    <div data-type=\"title\">\n      <ul>\n        <li>Solve an equation.<ul>\n            <li>Use properties of equality.</li>\n          </ul>\n        </li>\n        <li>Use the Distributive Property.</li>\n        <li>Simplify.</li>\n        <li>Combine like terms.</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n    <h4>Try It: Solving Equations and Creating Equivalent Equations</h4>\n    <p>Write two equivalent equations to \\( 2(x+4)= 12 \\).</p>\n    <p><span>Write down your answer, and then select the <strong>Solution</strong> button to compare your work.</span></p>\n  </div>\n</div><br>\n<div class=\"os-raise-ib-cta\" data-button-text=\"Solution\" data-fire-event=\"eventShow1\" data-schema-version=\"1.0\">\n  <div class=\"os-raise-ib-cta-content\">\n    <!-- INSERT ANY VALID HTML HERE -->\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"os-raise-ib-cta-prompt\">\n    <!-- INSERT ANY VALID HTML HERE -->\n  </div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"os-raise-ib-content\" data-schema-version=\"1.0\" data-wait-for-event=\"eventShow1\">\n  <p id=\"fs-id1168345252532\">Here are some possible ways to find equivalent equations to \\( 2(x+4)= 12 \\):</p>\n  <table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\">\n    <colgroup>\n      <col width=\"139\">\n      <col width=\"485\">\n      <col>\n    </colgroup>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Step 1</span></p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Simplify each side of the equation as much as possible.<br></span></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li><span>Use the Distributive Property to remove any parentheses.</span></li>\n            <li><span>Combine like terms.</span></li>\n          </ul>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\">\\( 2(x+4)= 12 \\)<br></p>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\">\\(&nbsp;2x +8 =12&nbsp;\\)</p>\n          <p><br></p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Step 2</span></p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Collect all the variable terms on one side of the equation.<br></span></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li><span>Use the Addition or Subtraction Property of Equality.</span></li>\n          </ul>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>\\( 2x +8 =12 \\)</span></p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Step 3</span></p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Collect all the constant terms on the other side of the equation.<br></span></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li><span>Use the Addition or Subtraction Property of Equality.</span></li>\n          </ul>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\">\\(2x +8 =12\\)</p>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;\\(&nbsp;-8&nbsp;\\)&nbsp; &nbsp; \\(&nbsp;-8&nbsp;\\)</p>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\">\\( 2x = 4 \\)</p>\n          <p><br></p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Step 4&nbsp;</span></p>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Make the coefficient of the variable term equal to 1.<br></span></p>\n          <ul>\n            <li><span>Use the Multiplication or Division Property of Equality.</span></li>\n            <li><span>State the solution to the equation.</span></li>\n          </ul>\n        </td>\n        <td>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;\\( 2x = 4 \\)</p>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\">\\( \\frac{2x}{2} = \\frac{4}{2} \\)</p>\n          <p dir=\"ltr\">\\(&nbsp;x=2&nbsp;\\)</p>\n          <p><br></p>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <div><br>\n    <p>How did you do? Know that you learn more from wrong answers than from right answers! Wrong answers help us find flaws in our thinking. Take a minute to think about <em>why</em> you got the question wrong. Then you won&rsquo;t get this type of question wrong again!</p>\n  </div>\n</div>"
    }
